TY  - JOUR
T1  - Turning Up the Heat: The Discouraging Effect of Competition in Contests
AU  - Fang, Dawei
AU  - Noe, Thomas
AU  - Strack, Philipp
Y1  - 2019/07/30
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/705670
DO  - 10.1086/705670
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1940
EP  - 1975
VL  - 128
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We study contests in which contestants are homogeneous and have convex effort costs. Increasing contest competitiveness, by making prizes more unequal, scaling up the competition, or adding new contestants, always discourages effort. These results have significant implications: although often criticized as evidence of laxity or cronyism, muting competition (e.g., adopting softer grading curves or less high-powered promotion systems) can both reduce inequality and increase output. Holding promotion contests at the division level rather than the firm level can boost employees? effort. Our results are also consistent with personnel policies that feature egalitarian pay systems and dismissal of worst-performing employees.
AB  - We study contests in which contestants are homogeneous and have convex effort costs. Increasing contest competitiveness, by making prizes more unequal, scaling up the competition, or adding new contestants, always discourages effort. These results have significant implications: although often criticized as evidence of laxity or cronyism, muting competition (e.g., adopting softer grading curves or less high-powered promotion systems) can both reduce inequality and increase output. Holding promotion contests at the division level rather than the firm level can boost employees? effort. Our results are also consistent with personnel policies that feature egalitarian pay systems and dismissal of worst-performing employees.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/705670
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/705670
Y2  - 2026/04/24
