TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Use of Regression Statistics to Analyze Imperfect Pricing Policies
AU  - Jacobsen, Mark R.
AU  - Knittel, Christopher R.
AU  - Sallee, James M.
AU  - van Benthem, Arthur A.
Y1  - 2019/07/23
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/705553
DO  - 10.1086/705553
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1826
EP  - 1876
VL  - 128
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Corrective taxes can solve many market failures, but actual policies frequently deviate from the theoretical ideal because of administrative or political constraints. We present a method to quantify the efficiency costs of constraints on externality-correcting policies or, more generally, the costs of imperfect pricing, using simple regression statistics. Under certain conditions, the R2 and the sum of squared residuals from a regression of true externalities on policy variables measure relative welfare gains from policies. We illustrate via four empirical applications: random mismeasurement of externalities, imperfect electricity pricing, heterogeneity in the longevity of energy-consuming durable goods, and imperfect spatial policy differentiation.
AB  - Corrective taxes can solve many market failures, but actual policies frequently deviate from the theoretical ideal because of administrative or political constraints. We present a method to quantify the efficiency costs of constraints on externality-correcting policies or, more generally, the costs of imperfect pricing, using simple regression statistics. Under certain conditions, the R2 and the sum of squared residuals from a regression of true externalities on policy variables measure relative welfare gains from policies. We illustrate via four empirical applications: random mismeasurement of externalities, imperfect electricity pricing, heterogeneity in the longevity of energy-consuming durable goods, and imperfect spatial policy differentiation.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/705553
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/705553
Y2  - 2026/04/24
